Our device agent reads a flat key=value config off the box, and values regularly need embedded newlines, tabs and raw bytes (MOTD banners, serial command prefixes), plus long values get wrapped with trailing-backslash line continuations. The current loader hand-waves all of that and mangles a fat-fingered escape silently; I've spent two evenings this month diffing configs byte by byte. I want the decoding layer done properly, as its own unit, so the loader can underline the exact offending backslash in its error output. 'Somewhere in this value' is not an error message.

Write kvunesc.h and kvunesc.c (C17, no malloc, no globals). test_kvunesc.c is the contract, `make test` is acceptance; that file, the Makefile and mintest.h are fixed.

API, exactly this — the loader already calls it:

    typedef enum {
        KV_OK = 0,
        KV_ERR_TRAILING_BACKSLASH,
        KV_ERR_UNKNOWN_ESCAPE,
        KV_ERR_BAD_HEX,
        KV_ERR_TRUNCATED_HEX,
        KV_ERR_NOSPACE
    } kv_status;

    typedef struct {
        kv_status status;
        size_t consumed;   /* bytes of src examined (see below) */
        size_t out_len;    /* decoded bytes written, may include NULs */
        size_t err_line;   /* 1-based physical line of the bad backslash */
        size_t err_col;    /* 1-based byte column of that backslash */
    } kv_result;

    kv_result kv_decode_value(const char *src, size_t start_line, size_t start_col,
                              char *out, size_t outsz);

The loader hands you a pointer to the first byte after the '=' plus that byte's 1-based line and column in the file. Scan until an unescaped '\n' or the terminating NUL, whichever comes first; consumed = the offset of that terminator (the newline itself is not consumed — the loader eats it).

Escapes: \n newline, \t tab, \\ backslash, \xHH exactly two hex digits in either case producing that byte (\x00 is legal, which is why out_len exists — decoded values can hold NULs; you still NUL-terminate at out[out_len]). A backslash immediately followed by a real newline is a line continuation: drop both, then also drop the run of spaces and tabs that indents the next physical line.

Errors, first one wins, and err_line/err_col always point at the backslash that opened the bad escape: backslash right before the terminating NUL is KV_ERR_TRAILING_BACKSLASH; \x that reaches the end of the value (NUL or unescaped newline) before two digits is KV_ERR_TRUNCATED_HEX; \x meeting any other non-hex byte is KV_ERR_BAD_HEX (hex digits must sit literally, immediately after the \x — continuations do not apply inside an escape); a backslash before anything else is KV_ERR_UNKNOWN_ESCAPE. KV_ERR_NOSPACE when out cannot hold the decoded bytes plus the NUL, with err_line/err_col both 0. On every error: out set to the empty string when outsz > 0, consumed and out_len both 0. On success err_line and err_col are 0.

Column bookkeeping is the whole point: columns count bytes, start_col applies to src[0], and after a continuation the first kept byte of the continued line is at column (number of skipped blanks + 1). The tests pin positions for errors sitting after multiple continuations with mixed space/tab indents — get those exact.
